From: Kevin Hao <kexin.hao@windriver.com>
Date: Tue, 19 Oct 2010 13:48:29 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 198/252] qman: use the old FQD/PFDR memory in the dump kernel

Since the dump kernel only use the memory reserved for it,
it is safe for the QMAN to still use the FQD/PFDR memory
set by the previous kernel. This will also make it easy
to reuse the QMAN in dump kernel.

Signed-off-by: Kevin Hao <kexin.hao@windriver.com>
---
 drivers/hwqueue/qman_config.c |    2 +-
 1 files changed, 1 insertions(+), 1 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/hwqueue/qman_config.c b/drivers/hwqueue/qman_config.c
index 0107f1b..392196f 100644
--- a/drivers/hwqueue/qman_config.c
+++ b/drivers/hwqueue/qman_config.c
@@ -463,7 +463,7 @@ static __init int parse_mem_property(struct device_node *node, const char *name,
 	return 0;
 }
 
-#ifdef CONFIG_KEXEC_POWERPC_SMP_BOOTABLE
+#if defined(CONFIG_KEXEC_POWERPC_SMP_BOOTABLE) && !defined(CONFIG_CRASH_DUMP)
 /* we're coming from a kexec reboot, of course the register will have a
  * non-zero value in it, but we want to reallocate the memory from the
  * new kernel, not use the old memory, which might be used for something
-- 
